description.narrative: (Liberia): .USAID's flagship government to government (G2G) agreement, the Fixed Amount Reimbursement Agreement (FARA), supports the Ministry of Health (MOH) to implement components of the Essential Package of Health Services (EPHS) focused on key high impact interventions in: malaria targeting children under five years and pregnant women; and reproductive, maternal, newborn, and child health, and family planning (RMNCH/FP). ..Specifically, FY 2019 funds will support MOH county health teams and health facilities in six counties to provide quality health services and improve health outcomes of mothers and children under five years. Malaria funds will be used to increase the percent of: (a) pregnant women receiving a third dose of intermittent preventive treatment during pregnancy for malaria and (b) women receiving insecticide-treated nets after delivery. Maternal Child Health funds will support increases in the percent of deliveries attended by skilled health personnel, postpartum women receiving postnatal care within 48 hours after delivery, and the percent of children under one year of age who are fully immunized. Family Planning and Reproductive Health funds will support an increase in clients counselled on family planning and the use of modern family planning methods. Additionally, funds will be used to improve service quality by building the capacities of district health teams to provide oversight and mentorship to health facilities, monitor and supervise health interventions through MOH's integrated supportive supervision, and develop and/or implement innovative approaches to improve referral systems as well as community engagement to improve health services. .FY 2019 funds will also focus on improving local capacity through training and mentorship of district and county health teams, and system strengthening of district and county health systems by the MOH and other USAID supported mechanisms. ...
